title: Texas Public Records Act Request: Flock Safety search audits, network sharing, and general order (Johnson County Sheriff)

communications.subject: Texas Public Information Act Request: Texas Public Records Act Request: Flock Safety search audits, network sharing, and general order (Johnson County Sheriff)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Texas Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records related to the department’s Flock Safety system:
1. Organization Audit in Flock. 
The report should include data logged from the period of December 1, 2024, to the date this request is processed. Per Flock's documentation, the Organization Audit is available within the Insights tab and is defined as searches done within the agency.

2. Network Audit in Flock.
The report should include data logged from the period of December 1, 2024, to the date this request is processed. Per Flock's documentation, the Network Audit is available within the Insights tab and is defined as searches of the organization’s Flock network by any agency in the Flock System.

3. A list of network share settings that include:
3a. Flock networks shared with me
3b. Networks that I’m sharing

Please provide records in their original electronic, machine readable format. For example, please provide csv or spreadsheet files where applicable. Please do not redirect me to your transparency portal.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Paul Tepper

communications.subject: RE: Texas Public Information Act Request: Texas Public Records Act Request: Flock Safety search audits, network sharing, and general order (Johnson County Sheriff)

2. Network Audit in Flock.
The report should include data logged from the period of December 1, 2024, to the date this request is processed. Per Flock's documentation, the Network Audit is available within the Insights tab and is defined as searches of the organization’s Flock network by any agency in the Flock System.
3. A list of network share settings that include:
3a. Flock networks shared with me
3b. Flock networks shared with me Devices List (Please see https://cdn.muckrock.com/foia_files/2022/11/17/CPRA_REQUEST.pdf
https://cdn.muckrock.com/foia_files/2022/11/09/1938_001.pdf as examples of the lists from other jurisdictions.
3c. Networks that I’m sharing

Please provide records in their original electronic, machine readable format. For example, please provide csv or spreadsheet files where applicable. Please do not redirect me to your transparency portal.

title: Forrest City ShotSpotter Contract

communications.subject: Arkansas Freedom of Information Act Request: Forrest City ShotSpotter Contract
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Arkansas Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

The most recent contract (i.e. council resolution, contract extension, contract amendments, cure notices, or other revisions to agreements) between the city and SoundThinking, Inc., formerly ShotSpotter, Inc.. This document(s) should include the total cost over the life of the contract and the current expiration date.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Sonny Albarado, a citizen of Arkansas, in coordination with Sophia Ludt.

title: R.I. Homicide Logs

communications.subject: Rhode Island Access to Public Records Act Request: R.I. Homicide Logs
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Rhode Island Access to Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

A copy of the State Police's Homicide logs, which should identify case numbers, detective names, weapon(s) used, location of homicide, motive and manner, and any other information the department has listed for homicides. I request such records for homicides that took place between Jan. 1, 2020 to present.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Alexa Gagosz

title: South Carolina Freedom of Information Act. Request: South Carolina Freedom of Information Act. Request: Pepsi and Coke (University Of South Carolina Upstate)

communications.subject: South Carolina Public Records Law Request: South Carolina Freedom of Information Act. Request: South Carolina Freedom of Information Act. Request: Pepsi and Coke (University Of South Carolina Upstate)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the { Rhode Island Freedom of Information Act. }, I hereby request the following records:

- A copy of any and all contracts (including associated amendments and exhibits) awarded to Pepsi, Coca-Cola, or any subdivision thereof, for the provision of beverages or other goods in any facilities under the purview of this organization, including all activities and buildings associated with athletics, sports, dining services, or otherwise. If this agency does not have a contract with either of the named companies, please provide the equivalent agreement with the currently employed company.
- If the contract(s) was cancelled, any and all materials related to its cancellation.
- If the contract was cancelled, the statement from the university about cancellation.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within { 5 days }.

Sincerely,

{ Kayla Henson }

title: Defector Nguyen Thanh Son / JCRC Refugee Reference T84-278

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Defector Nguyen Thanh Son / JCRC Refugee Reference T84-278
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, 5 U.S.C. § 552, I hereby request access to records concerning Nguyen Thanh Son, also known as Son Nguyen Tan or Manh Du, a North Vietnamese defector who provided information about American POWs in the Ba To region, Quang Ngai Province, South Vietnam after the ceasefire agreement in 1973. Nguyen Thanh Son may also be the refugee known as 'Son Nguyen Tan' with JCRC reference number T84-278, who was a former ARVN SSG, Interpreter for the 3rd Bde TF, US 4th Inf Div.

Specifically, I am seeking:

1. All interrogation reports, debriefing documents, recordings (including transcripts in any language) and communications related to Nguyen Thanh Son’s defection, particularly those dated on or after March 22, 1973. 

The following artefacts from the National Archives pertaining to this request are provided for reference: 

- AMEMBASSY SAIGON message 111035Z JUN 73 to SECSTATE IMMEDIATE 2984 [https://www.loc.gov/item/powmia/pwmaster_117133/]

- USDAO SGN RVN message dated 110900Z JUN 73 referencing  [https://www.loc.gov/item/powmia/pwmaster_65641/]

- USDAO SGN RVN message dated JUN 5, 1973  [https://www.loc.gov/item/powmia/pwmaster_44839/]

2. Records or intelligence reports regarding sightings of American POWs in Vietnam mentioned by Nguyen Thanh Son on or after March 1973.

3. Investigation and intelligence reports evaluating the credibility of Nguyen Thanh Son’s claims about American POWs.

4. Internal memos and briefings citing Nguyen Thanh Son’s information on American POWs in Vietnam.

5. Correspondence between US government agencies regarding Nguyen Thanh Son’s defection and the resulting analyses regarding his claims.

6. All files and documentation of the refugee with JCRC reference number T84-278 such as those referenced in the National Archives: 

- JCRC-LNB memo to JCRC 25 NOV 1984 [https://www.loc.gov/item/powmia/pwmaster_31991/]

- REPLY TO REQUEST FOR INFORMATION ON SOURCE. [https://www.loc.gov/item/powmia/pwmaster_31993/]

- NVA DEFECTOR DETAILS PLOT. REVEAL ICCS SABOTAGE ORDERS, FROM NEW YORK TIMES. [https://www.loc.gov/item/powmia/pwmaster_31994/]


If there are any fees for searching or copying these records, please inform me if the cost will exceed $50. However, I would also like to request a waiver of all fees in accordance with 5 U.S.C. § 552(a)(4)(A)(iii). I am a private individual seeking information for personal purposes and not for commercial use. Disclosure of the requested information is in the public interest because it is likely to contribute significantly to public understanding of government operations and activities regarding this issue.

If any portion of the information is exempt from disclosure, please provide me with the non-exempt portions. If the requested records are in an electronic format, I would prefer to receive them via email or on a CD-ROM if email is not feasible.

Please acknowledge receipt of this request and provide me with an estimated completion date. 

Thank you for your attention to this matter. I look forward to your response.

Sincerely,

Benjamin Bagley

title: Contract Documents for GPS at Massachusetts Sheriffs Offices (Middlesex County Sheriff's Office)

communications.subject: Massachusetts Public Records Law Request: Contract Documents for GPS at Massachusetts Sheriffs Offices (Middlesex County Sheriff's Office)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Massachusetts Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

All contract documents related to your GPS monitoring program, including the name(s) of the GPS provider(s) your office contracts with. I also request a copy of the current contract with your GPS provider(s), and any regulations, policies, or procedures your office uses to govern the GPS program.

I also request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as we believe this request is in the public interest, as suggested but not stipulated by the recommendations of the Massachusetts Supervisor of Public Records. The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, and is not made for commercial usage.

I expect the request to be filled in an accessible format, including for screen readers, which provide text-to-speech for persons unable to read print. Files that are not accessible to screen readers include, for example, .pdf image files as well as physical documents.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Joshua Dankoff

communications.subject: RE: California Public Records Act Request: Shooting Records
communications.communication:
Hello, 

Court decisions say you have to release the names of officers, their names do not jeopardize an investigation, and are subject to disclosure. The public interest outweighs the 
 https://law.justia.com/cases/california/supreme-court/2014/s200872.html 

Furthermore, SB1421 requires the department to release records related to police shootings. They are exempt from permanent disclosure as an investigatory record. There is no right to privacy in cases of officer shootings. 
https://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/billTextClient.xhtml?bill_id=201720180SB1421

Upon invoking this post-60-day delay, and at subsequent 180-day intervals for each subsequent delay, the Departments must provide in writing to the requester, the specific basis for the Departments' determination that it has reason to believe that disclosure will interfere with the criminal investigation of the officer who engaged in misconduct or used force, or of someone other than the officer who used force. In addition, this writing must include the estimated date for disclosure of the withheld information. In any event, the Departments must provide the information when the specific basis for withholding is resolved, the investigation or proceeding is no longer active, and in no case later than 18 months following the use of force incident, whichever occurs sooner. Cal. Penal Code § 832.7(b)(8)(A)(ii).

At most, you have 18 months since July 4th, 2024, to delay the release.  You must provide the above requirements for the continued delay in releasing records. 

Thank you

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: Washington State Electric Vehicle Charging Program
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records related to all awardees of the state's Electric Vehicle Charging Program. For each grant recipient, I request:

* Grant applications
* Progress reports, milestone reports, and other periodic reporting documents
* Documents containing proposed and actual charging station locations
* Budget documents, including proposed and actual expenditures
* Amendments or modifications to original grant agreements
* Final project completion reports, if available

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Cody Harris

communications.subject: PUBLIC RECORD REQUEST :: P001706-022425
communications.communication:
Dear Cody Harris: 
Thank you for submitting your request for the following records: Records Requested: To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records related to all awardees of the state's Electric Vehicle Charging Program. For each grant recipient, I request:

* Grant applications
* Progress reports, milestone reports, and other periodic reporting documents
* Documents containing proposed and actual charging station locations
* Budget documents, including proposed and actual expenditures
* Amendments or modifications to original grant agreements
* Final project completion reports, if available

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Cody Harris

Upload documents directly: https://accounts.muckrock.com/accounts/login/?next=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.muckrock.com%2Faccounts%2Flogin%2F%3Fnext%3D%252Faccounts%252Fagency_login%252Fdepartment-of-commerce-5573%252Fwashington-state-electric-vehicle-charging-program-181987%252F%253Femail%253Dcommercewa%252540govqa.us&url_auth_token=AABCmuzFKtmgaEDpBVZ8oaaurWw%3A1tmVcc%3AK_8lGdblEB62snyonBN54QiuRaT9ULcqLLafr2eq5hA 
 
Your request was received in this office on 2/24/2025 and given the reference number P001706-022425 for tracking purposes. 
Your request is being processed in accordance with the State of Washington Public Records Act, Chapter 42.56 RCW.  You will be contacted within five (5) business days with an update as to when the responsive records will be available.  You can monitor the progress of your request at the link below and you'll receive an email when your request has been completed. 
PLEASE NOTE: The State of Washington Public Records Act, Chapter 42.56 RCW, does not require a governmental body to create new information, to do legal research, or to answer questions. 
 
Again, thank you for your interest in public records of Department of Commerce. 
Department of Commerce

In conducting a search for records, we would like to determine whether there is any further clarification you would like to provide in order for us to best respond to your request.

communications.subject: RE: Washington Public Records Act Request #P001706-022425
communications.communication:
Thank you for the prompt response.

My understanding, per publicly available information on the Electric Vehicle Charging Program, is that to date there has been one round of contracts awarded since the program began and that a second round has not yet opened for applications.

If my understanding that there has so far only been one contracts round completed is correct, then your interpretation of my request as pertaining to the most recent (and only) contracts round is acceptable.

If there has been more than one round, then I will clarify that my request pertains to the time period when the program began, which is reportedly Tuesday, September 26, 2023, to February 1, 2024, when an announcement of the program’s awardees was made.

Thank you,
~Cody Harris

title: Fire Truck Repair (Oakland Fire Department)

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Fire Truck Repair (Oakland Fire Department)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Recent media reports suggest that the cost of purchasing and maintaining fire trucks has increased in recent years: https://www.thebignewsletter.com/p/did-a-private-equity-fire-truck-roll?utm_source=post-email-title&publication_id=11524&post_id=155466046&utm_campaign=email-post-title&isFreemail=true&r=44j01&triedRedirect=true&utm_medium=email

Therefore, I request the following:

A list of all fire truck repair parts purchased by this fire department in for the years 2005, 2010, 2015, 2020, 2024, and 2025, along with their prices.
Planned and actual budgets for fire equipment service and parts for 2005, 2010, 2015, 2020, 2024, and 2025 

Any repair manuals, repair part catalogs, repair invoices, or repair contracts created by this fire department or received by third parties for the years 2005, 2010, 2015, 2020, 2024, and 2025

A copy of any warranties, non-disclosure agreements, contracts, liability waivers, insurance agreements, Requests for Proposals, Responses to Requests for Proposal, Memorandums of Understanding, Letters of Interest, usage policies, or informal agreements between the fire department and American Industrial Partners or REV Group.

A copy of any reports to legislative bodies or annual reports that mention American Industrial Partners or Rev Group sent to oversight bodies.
Communications, contracts, and presentations sent to/from/between REV Group (including E-ONE, KME, Ferrara, Spartan, Smeal, LTI) or Pierce (@piercemfg.com) and this department)

Please try to include any other miscellaneous documents that facilitate this department's repair of fire trucks that don’t neatly fit into the categories above. Except where specifically noted (requests #1, 2, and 3), please search between January 1, 2024 and the time this request is published.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

title: Request for Correctional Mental Health Staff Directory and Contact Information (Department of Corrections)

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: Request for Correctional Mental Health Staff Directory and Contact Information (Department of Corrections)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

I am requesting a list of currently employed mental health professionals within your state's Department of Corrections or its subsidiary agencies, as well as their contact information.

Specifically, I am requesting:

- Full names
- Job titles
- Assigned correctional facility
- Government-issued email addresses
- Government-issued phone numbers (direct desk numbers if available, otherwise department phone numbers with or without extensions)
- Department/division (e.g. Behavioral Health, Mental Health Services)

This request applies to the following roles: rehabilitative program coordinators, licensed psychologists, psychiatrists, clinical social workers, and other licensed mental health professionals serving incarcerated populations in state-operated facilities.

If available, I request this information be provided in a machine-readable format such as CSV or Excel.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Andrew Ma

communications.subject: [Records Center] Public Records Request :: P052632-051525
communications.communication:
--- Please respond above this line --- 

Andrew Ma: 

I acknowledge receipt of your public records request dated May 15, 2025, and received in our office on May 16, 2025. We have assigned this request a tracking number of P-52632.  Please refer to this number in all future communications regarding this request. 

You state your request to be for the following records: 
a list of currently employed mental health professionals within your state's Department of Corrections or its subsidiary agencies, as well as their contact information. 

Specifically, I am requesting: 

- Full names 
- Job titles 
- Assigned correctional facility 
- Government-issued email addresses 
- Government-issued phone numbers (direct desk numbers if available, otherwise department phone numbers with or without extensions) 
- Department/division (e.g. Behavioral Health, Mental Health Services) 

This request applies to the following roles: rehabilitative program coordinators, licensed psychologists, psychiatrists, clinical social workers, and other licensed mental health professionals serving incarcerated populations in state-operated facilities 

I interpret your request to be for the following records, current as of May 16, 2025 (the day your request was received): 

• A list of the following data for all Department of Correction (DOC) licensed psychologists, psychiatrists, mental health providers, and other behavioral health providers: 
o Full names 
o Job titles 
o Assigned work location 
o DOC issued phone # 
o DOC issued email address 

If my interpretation is incorrect, please notify through the request portal or email me at tonja.monroe@doc1.wa.gov. It is noted that you have requested these records in an Excel or CSV format, this request cannot always be accommodated since these formats cannot hold redactions should those be necessary. We will determine if this is possible once the records have been gathered. (mailto:tonja.monroe@doc1.wa.gov) 

Before proceeding with disclosure of the requested list of information, can you please clarify by filling out the uploaded , letting us know about your Commercial Purposes Declaration intended use of the records being requested. 

Please be advised that if I do not hear back from you within 30 days, this request will be administratively closed. This means that the Department will not further address the request, and that will be the date from which the PRA’s on-year statute of limitations to seek judicial review starts to run. 

Sincerely, 
Tonja Monroe, Public Records Specialist

Thank you for your message and for clearly outlining the scope of the request — your interpretation is accurate.

I’ve completed and attached the Commercial Purposes Declaration, confirming that this request is not for a commercial purpose. The records are being requested to support outreach for a free, volunteer-led mindfulness and rehabilitation program for incarcerated individuals.

While I originally requested the records in Excel or CSV format, I completely understand that those formats may not accommodate redactions. If necessary, I’m happy to receive the records in PDF format instead.

Please let me know if anything further is needed. I appreciate your time and assistance.

Warm regards,
Andrew Ma

title: Racial Categories x Disability

communications.subject: Illinois Freedom of Information Act. Request: Racial Categories x Disability
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request the following records:

1. The total number of students who have IEPs in school years 2024/2025 to date by disability category broken down by race per disability category. (Disability x Ethnicity)

This should produce a primary disability category and show the racial/ethnic categories within that disability (Amer. Indian/Alaskan Native, Asian, Black, Hawaiian or Pacific Islander, Hispanic, Multiracial, Not Available, White, Blank). For example, if the primary disability is Autism, there should be a column with the number of students per racial/ethnic category who have a primary disability of autism. This applies to all of the disability categories. 

This request is made on behalf of The FOIA Bakery. Because this request is in the public interest for Illinois nonprofit The FOIA Bakery’s work to advocate for public education, please waive any fees in accordance with 5 ILCS § 140/6(c). Feel free to contact me with any questions, or if clarification is needed.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Miriam Bhimani

communications.communication: I'm sorry I lost track of this!  As you know, this is a tiny jurisdiction.  I have no responsive documents, but I only keep records of violations of criminal law; for violations of internal policy, any records would be kept by the sheriff's office.  You can reach the person you need to reach there at grassethr@co.wahkiakum.wa.us.

communications.subject: Your public record request to Wahkiakum County
communications.communication:
To:  189423-07971816@requests.muckrock.com
Hi, you asked me for Brady lists and “any and all records regarding substantiated allegations of misconduct or violations of internal department policy or criminal law by specific law enforcement officers.”
I already responded that Wahkiakum County has no Brady list.  I now attach all records the sheriff’s office can find regarding substantiated allegations of misconduct or violations.  (Neither of the deputies concerned are working for the sheriff’s office and therefore neither are on my Brady list.)  The incidents occurred long ago and now fall outside the retention schedule set for us by the Washington State Archives, which means they could have been destroyed, but some materials were discovered and I reproduce them for you here.  The first documents ending 3050 and 3060, concern Josh Grasseth, who came back to town after a stint working for the S’Kallam tribal police and then a few years in the private sector and who is now running for sheriff.  The rest regard Bill Tawater, who retired and is now a pillar of the local American Legion post.
I believe this is all we have, but since these documents were found in places other than the likely places such documents would be found, we will keep looking and turn over to you anything responsive that we find.  In the expectation that we will not find anything, and for the purposes of establishing a legal statute of limitations, however, I am closing this request as of today.  If you object or have further questions, please contact me.
Among the papers we found is one relevant page I am not sending on.  It is a 2016 email from me that contains legal advice relevant to your request, and it is privileged and exempt from the Public Records Act.  The privilege is established by RCW 5.60.060(2)(a), which is an "other statute" that exempts or prohibits disclosure pursuant to RCW 42.56.070(1).
Thank you for your inquiry.  Please get back in touch if you have any questions or would like to make another request.  Have a great day!

communications.subject: RE: FOIA Request -- 7/7/25 [#F25250]
communications.communication:
Anonymous:
Thank you for the request which was considered received on July 7, 2025. Please note the University was closed on July 3 and 4, 2025, in observance of the Independence Day holiday.
In final response your request is denied as the University does not process requests from anonymous individuals. We are required to report to the Secretary of State the legal name of individuals asking for the information given that this process concerns an action against a state entity. WVFOIA Procedure 1 and W. Va. Code § 29B-1-3(c) (stating that the custodian may make reasonable rules and regulations necessary for the protection of the records and to prevent interference with the regular discharge of his or her duties). See also W. Va. Code § 29B-1-3(f), § 61-5-27, § 61-5-27A, and Code of State Rules § 153-52-3.5 (“Information required to be entered into the database shall be the following: . . . ;3.5.b. The name of the person or entity making the request;”).
West Virginia University reserves its right to exercise any and all applicable exemptions under W. Va. Code § 29B-1-4, privileges, or defenses, as appropriate. Further, as required by W. Va. Code § 29B-1-3(d),<https://code.wvlegislature.gov/29B-1-3/> please be advised that this request is at an end.

Dr. David May:
This e-mail is a final response concerning your West Virginia Freedom of Information Act request received on July 16, 2025, requesting the “academic dishonesty reports from the beginning of the Fall 2021 semester to the end of the Spring 2025 Semester, organized by university college.”

Please note there is not a document already created or a spreadsheet containing the information in the manner you have requested. See Daily Gazette Co. v. Withrow, 177 W. Va. 110, 119 n.9, 350 S.E.2d 738, 746 n.9 (1986) (“There is no obligation under the State FOIA to create any particular record, but only to provide access to a public record already created[.]”).

That said there was a power point slide presented to the faculty senate that is partially responsive to your request.  Please see the attached one (1) page responsive document Bates numbered WVU FOIA #25250-001.

Please note that regardless of the production of these or other related documents, West Virginia University reserves its right to exercise any and all applicable exemptions under W. Va. Code § 29B-1-4, privileges, or defenses, as appropriate.  Further, as required by W. Va. Code § 29B-1-3(d),<https://code.wvlegislature.gov/29B-1-3/> please be advised that this request is now at an end.

Thank you.

FOIA OFFICER
West Virginia University

title: Contract Documents for GPS at Massachusetts Sheriffs Offices (Barnstable County Sheriff's Office)

communications.subject: Massachusetts Public Records Law Request: Contract Documents for GPS at Massachusetts Sheriffs Offices (Barnstable County Sheriff's Office)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Massachusetts Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

All contract documents related to your GPS monitoring program, including the name(s) of the GPS provider(s) your office contracts with. I also request a copy of the current contract with your GPS provider(s), and any regulations, policies, or procedures your office uses to govern the GPS program.

I also request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as we believe this request is in the public interest, as suggested but not stipulated by the recommendations of the Massachusetts Supervisor of Public Records. The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, and is not made for commercial usage.

I expect the request to be filled in an accessible format, including for screen readers, which provide text-to-speech for persons unable to read print. Files that are not accessible to screen readers include, for example, .pdf image files as well as physical documents.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Joshua Dankoff

title: Safety National Complaints (Division of Insurance)

communications.subject: Massachusetts Public Records Law Request: Safety National Complaints (Division of Insurance)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Massachusetts Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

I am requesting access to all records in your possession from January 1, 2014, through the present concerning complaints, investigations, or regulatory actions involving Safety National Casualty Corporation, including any affiliated entities such as Safety Specialty Insurance Company and Sedgwick Claims Management Services, Inc. 

Specifically, I request copies of all consumer complaints alleging claim denials, delays, bad faith practices, misrepresentation of coverage, or failure to defend or indemnify insureds; any related correspondence or internal assessments; all regulatory enforcement actions, including market conduct examinations, administrative penalties, consent orders, fines, stipulations, or notices of violation; and any internal memoranda, emails, audit findings, or documentation regarding systemic or repeated misconduct. I also seek any statistical reports, dashboards, or complaint trend summaries reflecting activity related to Safety National during this period.

I also request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as we believe this request is in the public interest, as suggested but not stipulated by the recommendations of the Massachusetts Supervisor of Public Records. The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, and is not made for commercial usage.

I expect the request to be filled in an accessible format, including for screen readers, which provide text-to-speech for persons unable to read print. Files that are not accessible to screen readers include, for example, .pdf image files as well as physical documents.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Matthew Fecteau

communications.subject: RE: Massachusetts Public Records Law Request: Safety National Complaints (Division of Insurance)
communications.communication:
Thank you for your patience, the documents have been sent via MOVEit, they are available to download for 35 days.  Please note that all identifying information relating to the complainant and any witnesses has been redacted, as that information is exempt from disclosure pursuant to M.G.L. c.4, §7(26)(a) and (f).  Commonly known as the statutory exemption, M.G.L. c.4, §7(26) (a) applies to records that are specifically or by necessary implication exempted from disclosure by statute.  M.G.L. c.93H, relating to the security of personal information, defines personal information as a residents name in combination with a financial account number and requires agencies to safeguard personal information.  Consumer complaint files contain individuals names associated with their insurance policy numbers, thus they contain personal information as defined by M.G.L. c.93H.  The Division of Insurance is required by this statute to maintain the confidentiality of personal information.   In addition, the names of the complainants have been redacted in order to maintain the confidentiality of their identity pursuant to M.G.L. c.4, §7(26) (f), commonly known as the investigatory exemption.  This exemption is intended to allow investigative officials to provide an assurance of confidentiality to individuals so they will speak openly about matters under investigation.  Bougas v. Chief of Police, 371 Mass 59, 62 (1976).

Pursuant to M. G.L. c.66, §10A(a), you may appeal this response to the Supervisor of Public Records following the procedures set forth in 950 CMR 32.08, a copy of which is available at  http://www.mass.gov/courts/docs/lawlib/900-999cmr/950cmr32.pdf.  You may also file a civil action in accordance with M.G.L. c.66, §10A(c).

Mindy A. Merow Rubin
Counsel to the Commissioner and

title: Security Evaluation Criteria Used to Adopt SolarApp+

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Security Evaluation Criteria Used to Adopt SolarApp+
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act (Gov. Code § 6250 et seq.), I am requesting access to and copies of any and all records, communications, evaluations, or internal documents related to the City’s decision to implement or endorse the use of SolarApp+ for permitting solar projects.

In particular, I am seeking documents responsive to:
1. Any security assessments, audits, penetration tests, risk evaluations, or cybersecurity reviews conducted by or on behalf of the City prior to, during, or after adoption of SolarApp+.
2. All internal communications, staff emails, memos, or meeting notes discussing the security posture, data protection protocols, or vendor risk associated with SolarApp+.
3. Any contracts, MOUs, or agreements entered into between the City and SolarApp+ or its administering entities that reference system integrity, data handling, or compliance with information security standards.
4. Any communication with DOE, NREL, or associated contractors referencing security, risk, or due diligence in connection with SolarApp+ adoption.

For reference, the City's implementation of SolarApp+ is promoted on the following website: https://www.fairfield.ca.gov/government/city-departments/community-development/building-safety/solar-app. We are aware that similar platforms have undergone extensive technical and security evaluations by the City prior to approval. This request seeks to understand whether the same level of scrutiny was applied in this case.

Please include records regardless of format (emails, PDFs, memos, scanned documents, etc.) and from all relevant staff or departments involved in the decision-making process.

If any part of this request is unclear or overly broad, I am happy to discuss ways to narrow or clarify it. If any portion of the request is being withheld or redacted, please cite the specific exemption and legal justification.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Ramon Vega

communications.subject: RE: New York Freedom of Information Law Request #R001537-031025
communications.communication:
Dear Records Access Officer:

This is an appeal of your determination on 7/03/25 regarding FOIL # R001537-031025

The office of the governor has constructively denied my request. The possible return date of July 31, 2025 -- and the lack of an explanation – is unreasonable, given the narrow scope of the request, originally submitted March 10.

Because of this appeal, the executive chamber is required by law to provide specific reasons within 10 business days explaining why this request cannot be filled, or else, must provide the records sought.

According to the Committee on Open Government, if a government entity acknowledges that a request has been received, but has failed to grant access by the specific date given beyond twenty business days, or if the specific date given is unreasonable, a request may be considered to have been constructively denied (see §89[4][a]). In such a circumstance, the denial may be appealed in accordance with §89(4)(a), which states in relevant part that:

“...any person denied access to a record may within thirty days appeal in writing such denial to the head, chief executive or governing body of the entity, or the person therefore designated by such head, chief executive, or governing body, who shall within ten business days of the receipt of such appeal fully explain in writing to the person requesting the record the reasons for further denial, or provide access to the record sought.”

I, on behalf of New York Focus, am requesting either you fill this FOIL request, or else provide a full explanation as to the reason for the denial, as required by law, of this public record.

Sincerely,
Julia Rock
New York Focus

title: Bodycam - El Cajon

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Bodycam - El Cajon
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

I am requesting all records related to the February 25, 2025, incident involving Richard Leyva in El Cajon, CA, where police discovered the body of Jamison Webster in the trunk of a vehicle following a pursuit and collision. Please provide all available body-worn camera footage, dashcam footage, 911 calls, radio traffic, surveillance video, arrest reports, incident reports, use-of-force documentation, and any other records or media generated in connection with this case. This request includes any related metadata and officer narratives.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Tavin Way

communications.subject: El Cajon Public Records Request for Police Department No. PRR25-494, Topic: General
communications.communication:
Thank you for contacting the El Cajon Police Department. We have received your request for information and will begin processing it. A response to this request will be sent in a timely manner as allowed by California Government Code Section 7922.535.  In unusual circumstances, that time period may be extended an additional 14 days. We make every effort to respond to requests for information as quickly as possible. Normal business hours (lobby open to public) are: 
Monday-Thursday, 8:00am-5:00pm, and every other Friday, 9:00am-5:00pm. To check on the status of your request, return to the Public Records site and click on Lookup Request. *NOTE: At "Lookup Request", enter the tracking number, and click on the Submit button (Enter key will not work). You will be prompted for this tracking number, PRR25-494, along with your email, 189270-75817897@requests.muckrock.com

communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

A copy of FBI file 65-HQ-57668, on the interception of diplomatic communications from the Yugoslavian government during World War II.

Please conduct a search of the Central Records System and the Alexandria Record s Center, including but not limited to the Electronic Surveillance (ELSUR) Indices, the Microphone Surveillance (MISUR) Indices, the Physical Surveillance (FISUR) Indices, and the Technical Surveillance (TESUR) Indices, for both main-file records and cross-reference records for all relevant names, individuals, agencies and companies. If any potentially responsive records have been destroyed and/or transferred to NARA, then I request copies of the destruction or transfer slips as well as any other documentation relating to, mentioning or describing said transfer or destruction, to include but not be limited to confirmation that the Bureau has no other copies of said records. If previously released records are available, then I request a rolling release consisting of those records while additional records are located and processed for release.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Paul Galante

The FBI's FOIPA Program is searching the FBI's indices for potentially responsive documents.
You may be contacted via formal letter for all fees and/or negotiation issues that may apply.

NOTE: Recent requests are entered into the FOIPA database in the order that they are received. Before you can check the status, you must have received correspondence assigning a FOIPA request number and the information transferred to the online database. Status information is updated weekly. If a request has been closed within the last six months the online database will display the following: The FOIPA number entered has been closed, and appropriate correspondence has been sent to the address on file.

Estimated Dates of Completion
Requests are processed in the order in which they are received through our multi-track processing system.  Requests are divided into two primary tracks--simple (under 50 pages of potentially responsive documents) and complex (over 50 pages of potentially responsive documents).  Complex requests are further divided into medium, large, and extra-large sub-tracks based upon request size.  Simple track requests typically require the least amount of time to process.  Currently, simple track cases average approximately 152 days from the date of receipt for processing.  Our complex requests in the medium processing track are currently averaging 922 days, large processing track are currently averaging approximately 1,964 days, and extra-large processing track are currently averaging 2,360 days for processing.

Respectfully,

Public Information Officer
FBI - Information Management Division
200 Constitution Drive
Winchester, VA  22602
O: (540) 868-4593
E: foipaquestions@fbi.gov<mailto:foipaquestions@fbi.gov>

Do you have further questions about the FOI/PA process? Visit us at http://www.fbi.gov/foia

Please check the status of your request online at https://vault.fbi.gov/fdps-1/@@search-fdps    Status updates are performed on a weekly basis.

Note:  This is a non-emergency email address.  If this is an emergency, please call 911 directly.  If you need to report a tip for immediate action, please contact FBI Tips at http://tips.fbi.gov/ or reach out to your local field office.

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Emails Mentioning "Embargo" 2020-2021 (FDA Office of Media Affairs)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

1. All emails that include and/or contain the word "embargo" that were sent to, from, and/or between any of the following email addresses between the dates of 3/1/2020 and the date this request is ultimately processed:

abigail.Capobianco@fda.hhs.gov

jeremy.kahn@fda.hhs.gov
kimberly.DiFonzo@fda.hhs.gov
kristin.jarrell@fda.hhs.gov
Lauren-Jei.McCarthy@fda.hhs.gov
lindsey.okeefe@fda.hhs.gov
lyndsay.meyer@fda.hhs.gov
megan.mcseveney@fda.hhs.gov
michael.felberbaum@fda.hhs.gov
monique.Richards@fda.hhs.gov
nathan.arnold@fda.hhs.gov
nicole.mueller@fda.hhs.gov
peter.Cassell@fda.hhs.gov
sarah.Peddicord@fda.hhs.gov
shannon.Hatch@fda.hhs.gov
shirley.Simson@fda.hhs.gov
stephanie.caccomo@fda.hhs.gov
tara.rabin@fda.hhs.gov
usfda@public.govdelivery.com
veronika.Pfaeffle@fda.hhs.gov

Please also make sure to include all attachments to those emails.

None of the keywords cited in this request should be interpreted by your agency as being case sensitive during the search and retrieval process.

When delivering the responsive documents related to this request, please make sure to specifically certify that no other responsive documents exist beyond those provided by your agency as part of this request.

The requested documents and information will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In order to help determine my status to assess fees, you should know that I am a freelance journalist whose work is published frequently by print and digital news outlets and magazines. I have previously been classified as a media requester by other federal agencies, including the CDC, when requesting information under the FOIA. You can view my work at www.erinmariemiller.com/clips. As a member of the media, I request a waiver of all fees. 

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I am willing to pay up to $25 for the requested information. If there is a fee that exceeds that amount, please notify me prior to initiating work on the request.

I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Erin Miller

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #2022-98
communications.communication:
FDA FOIA Public Liaison
Office of the Executive Secretariat
US Food Administration
5630 Fishers Lane, Room 1050

Re: APPEAL - Freedom of Information Act


To Whom It May Concern:

This is an appeal under the Freedom of Information Act regarding FDA FOIA Control #: 2022-98.

On Dec. 28, 2021, I requested records under the Freedom of Information Act from the FDA pertaining to "All emails that include and/or contain the word 'embargo' that were sent to, from, and/or between specific email addresses between the dates of 3/1/2020 and the date this request is ultimately processed, including their attachments." I also provided a specific list of email addresses belonging to officials at the FDA.

On Dec. 29, 2021, I received confirmation from the FDA that my request had been received and was provided with reference number FDA2179960.

On Jan. 4, 2022, I received an acknowledgement letter from director Sarah Kotler letting me know that the agency would respond to my request with a determination and let me know about fees, and informing me that the agency needed an extra 10 days to respond.

On Jan. 5, 2022, Sarah Kotler contacted me asking to speak with me by phone about my request.

On Jan. 6, 2022, I called the number Ms. Kotler had provided to me but was unable to reach her.

On Jan. 7, 2022, I finally spoke with Ms. Kotler by phone. She recommended that I narrow my search parameters down to the following to speed up the process of retrieving the requested information: "All emails that include and/or contain the word 'embargo' that were sent to, from, and/or between the following email addresses between the dates of 3/1/2020 and the date this request is ultimately processed: heidi.Rebello@fda.hhs.gov ; michael.felberbaum@fda.hhs.gov." 

I agreed to Ms. Kotler's recommendation to narrow the request to the above parameters by phone, and then sent a follow-up email immediately following our conversation confirming the same.

After my phone conversation with Ms. Kotler, my email address was suddenly classified as spam by the FDA. Because of that, my follow-up emails would not go through to Ms. Kotler. Instead, a traditional letter was sent by mail, which Ms. Kotler confirmed receipt of in an email sent to me on 1/25/2022.

It is now June 28, 2022 and I still have not received a determination letter for my request. I assume the request was approved, because Ms. Kotler sent an email response to my follow-up questions on 3/28/2022 and 4/27/2022 letting me know the agency was preparing a significant volume of records. However, I was never provided with a determination letter letting me know whether my request was approved or denied, or informing me of my fee status as a media requester.

As far as I am aware, the FDA is required by the FOIA to provide me with a determination about my request status and my fee status within 30 days of my request, both of which I still have not received over six months later.

I have attached copies of the only two letters I've received from Ms. Kotler regarding FDA FOIA Control #: 2022-98.

If you have any questions while handling this appeal, you can contact me at the email address listed below. I would prefer that all communications related to this appeal be in writing if possible, so I am not providing a phone number.

Thank you for your consideration of this appeal.


Sincerely,

Erin Miller
122415-50044888@requests.muckrock.com
MuckRock News DEPT MR 122415 411A Highland Ave
Somerville MA 02144-2516 US

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #2022-98
communications.communication:
Hi Christa,

Thank you for following up about FOI Request FOI# 2022-98. I am still very interested in receiving the records I requested from your agency via that FOIA request.

As far as your question asking for "a topic" related to the records I am seeking, please refer to this article in Scientific American: https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/how-the-fda-manipulates-the-media

As far as your question about specific keywords to search for, please follow the instructions in my original request and simply search for the term "embargo." You may also include "embargoes" and "embargoed," in addition to "embargo," if you think it might turn up additional records (although, presumably, a search for "embargo" should automatically include those additional terms).

Finally, as a reminder, I submitted this FOIA request to your agency on Dec. 28, 2021. It is now January 25, 2025. In over four years, your agency still has not provided me with the responsive records for this request. 

Given the extraordinary amount of time that has lapsed between the submission of my FOIA request and today's date, I believe it is appropriate to remind your agency of its duty to transparency under the FOIA, including your duty to make public records "promptly available" to requesters after a determination has been issued by your agency (which typically occurs within 20 days of the initial request, per  5 U.S.C. § 552(a)(6)(A)).

On 2/24/2022, Sarah B. Kotler emailed me about this request, stating: "The assigned office is currently searching for responsive records." On 3/28/2022, Sarah B. Kotler followed up again, stating: "We are in the process of collecting records for this request." 

It has been almost three years since Ms. Kotler emailed me those updates about my FOIA request.

Per  5 U.S.C. § 552(a)(6)(C)(i), agencies must provide requested records "promptly" after issuing a determination: "Any person making a request to any agency for records under paragraph (1), (2), or (3) of this subsection shall be deemed to have exhausted his administrative remedies with respect to such request if the agency fails to comply with the applicable time limit provisions of this paragraph. If the Government can show exceptional circumstances exist and that the agency is exercising due diligence in responding to the request, the court may retain jurisdiction and allow the agency additional time to complete its review of the records. Upon any determination by an agency to comply with a request for records, the records shall be made promptly available to such person making such request. Any notification of denial of any request for records under this subsection shall set forth the names and titles or positions of each person responsible for the denial of such request."

Even in cases of supposed "extraordinary circumstances," the Court of Appeals for the D.C. Circuit Court has already addressed the problem of unusually long delays in making public records available to requesters. In Citizens for Responsibility & Ethics in Washington v. Fed. Election Comm'n, 711 F.3d 180, 188 (D.C. Cir. 2013), the Court stated: 

"Second, the statute requires that the agency immediately notify the requester of the right 'to appeal to the head of the agency any adverse determination.- Id. The requirement that the agency notify the requester about administrative appeal rights further indicates that the “determination” must be substantive, not just a statement of a future intent to produce non-exempt responsive documents. Otherwise, this right of administrative appeal would make little sense because there would be nothing to appeal at the time the agency makes its supposed 'determination' in response to a properly filed FOIA request.

"This critical point both highlights and unravels the maneuver that the FEC (backed by the Department of Justice) is attempting here. Under the FEC's theory, an agency could respond to a request within 20 working days in terms not susceptible to immediate administrative appeal—by simply stating, in essence, that it will produce documents and claim exemptions over withheld documents in the future. Then, the agency could process the request at its leisure, free from any timelines. All the while, the agency's actions would remain immune from suit because the requester would not yet have been able to appeal and exhaust administrative appeal remedies. Therein lies the Catch–22 that the agency seeks to jam into FOIA: A requester cannot appeal within the agency because the agency has not provided the necessary information. Yet the requester cannot go to court because the requester has not appealed within the agency. Although the agency may desire to keep FOIA requests bottled up in limbo for months or years on end, the statute simply does not countenance such a system, as we read the statutory text." (Citizens for Responsibility & Ethics in Wash. v. Fed. Election Comm'n, 711 F.3d 180, 186-87 (D.C. Cir. 2013))

Keeping in mind the laws and court rulings cited above, it is unacceptable that I have waited over four years to receive the requested records under this FOIA request.

That said, please be aware that if I have not received all of the requested records pertaining to this request by 1/31/2025, I will have no choice but to seek dispute resolution from the OGIS, per my rights as a requester under the federal FOIA. Should that happen, considering the amount of time that has lapsed between my original request, and the fact that there is a six-year statute of limitations for filing FOIA lawsuits against the federal government, there is also a strong chance that I will begin to seek legal counsel regarding this request at the same time.

Please feel free to contact me in writing at this email address if you have any further questions. I do not wish to be contacted by phone, as I am now requesting that all further communications be in writing moving forward, so that I may have legal documentation to provide to OGIS and possibly an attorney.

Sincerely,

Erin Marie Miller

Erin Miller

200 Independence Avenue, SW
Washington, D.C. 20201

APPEAL: FOIA Request - FDA FOIA Control #2022-98

March 12, 2025

Dear Paula Formoso,

I am writing to submit an appeal for a FOIA request that I submitted to the U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA) on December 8, 2021, which sought records of emails containing the word “embargo” that were sent to, from, and/or between a set of specific email addresses belonging to specific officials at FDA and HHS between the dates of March 1, 2020, and the date the FOIA request was ultimately processed. 

My request (FDA FOIA Control #2022-98) was acknowledged by Sarah B. Kotler, Director of the FDA Division of Freedom of Information, on January 4, 2022. Part of the responsive records related to my request were apparently referred to HHS for review in December 2023, but were never provided to me.

You can review my original request and my communications with the FDA’s FOIA office staff about this request on the MuckRock website (an online FOIA requester service and public database through which my request was filed), where you can also review scans of the FDA’s acknowledgement letters and the partial records related to my request: https://www.muckrock.com/foi/united-states-of-america-10/emails-mentioning-embargo-2020-2021-fda-office-of-media-affairs-122415/ 

To my knowledge, none of the acknowledgement letters I received related to this FOIA request provided a deadline for appeal. To date, the request has not been completed by HHS or FDA, and because of HHS and FDA’s unusually long delays in providing the requested records, I am appealing both agencies' responses to this request, which I believe violate the FOIA in spirit and letter.

On December 28, 2023 (over a year after my request was submitted), I received a small batch of records related to my request. In an email to me on the same date, Ms. Kotler explained the partial delivery of records and informed me that additional records would be released to me the following month (January 2024). Ms. Kotler also informed me in that email about other records related to my request that had been referred to HHS and told me those records would be made available to me after review by your agency. You can view Ms. Kotler’s email at the MuckRock link above, under the “Communications” tab.

As of today’s date, March 12, 2025, I have not received any more documents related to my FOIA request beyond the partial delivery in December 2023, described above, despite Sarah Kotler’s assurances that more records would be provided to me.

It is unclear to me whether the remainder of my request will ever be completed, as it has been over three years since I originally submitted this request to the FDA, and it has been over a year since the agency last produced a small portion of the requested records and referred additional records to HHS for review. As a result of the unusually lengthy delay in the production of the requested records by both agencies, I am submitting this appeal to both agencies' public liaisons for review.

Per 5 U.S.C. § 552(a)(6)(C)(i), agencies must provide requested records "promptly" after issuing a determination: "Any person making a request to any agency for records under paragraph (1), (2), or (3) of this subsection shall be deemed to have exhausted his administrative remedies with respect to such request if the agency fails to comply with the applicable time limit provisions of this paragraph. If the Government can show exceptional circumstances exist and that the agency is exercising due diligence in responding to the request, the court may retain jurisdiction and allow the agency additional time to complete its review of the records. Upon any determination by an agency to comply with a request for records, the records shall be made promptly available to such person making such request. Any notification of denial of any request for records under this subsection shall set forth the names and titles or positions of each person responsible for the denial of such request."

Even in cases of supposed "extraordinary circumstances," the Court of Appeals for the D.C. Circuit Court has already addressed the problem of unusually long delays in making public records available to requesters, which also addressed the strategic tactic of failing to deliver documents timely in order to prevent requesters from appealing or seeking recourse in federal court. In Citizens for Responsibility & Ethics in Washington v. Fed. Election Comm'n, 711 F.3d 180, 188 (D.C. Cir. 2013), the Court stated:

"Second, the statute requires that the agency immediately notify the requester of the right 'to appeal to the head of the agency any adverse determination.- Id. The requirement that the agency notify the requester about administrative appeal rights further indicates that the “determination” must be substantive, not just a statement of a future intent to produce non-exempt responsive documents. Otherwise, this right of administrative appeal would make little sense because there would be nothing to appeal at the time the agency makes its supposed 'determination' in response to a properly filed FOIA request.

"This critical point both highlights and unravels the maneuver that the FEC (backed by the Department of Justice) is attempting here. Under the FEC's theory, an agency could respond to a request within 20 working days in terms not susceptible to immediate administrative appeal—by simply stating, in essence, that it will produce documents and claim exemptions over withheld documents in the future. Then, the agency could process the request at its leisure, free from any timelines. All the while, the agency's actions would remain immune from suit because the requester would not yet have been able to appeal and exhaust administrative appeal remedies. Therein lies the Catch–22 that the agency seeks to jam into FOIA: A requester cannot appeal within the agency because the agency has not provided the necessary information. Yet the requester cannot go to court because the requester has not appealed within the agency. Although the agency may desire to keep FOIA requests bottled up in limbo for months or years on end, the statute simply does not countenance such a system, as we read the statutory text." Citizens for Responsibility & Ethics in Wash. v. Fed. Election Comm'n, 711 F.3d 180, 186-87 (D.C. Cir. 2013).

Later in the decision, the Court went on to state: “Put simply, the unusual circumstances provision to extend the time for making a 'determination' makes sense only if the statute contemplates that responsive documents must be collected and examined, and decisions made about which to produce, in order for the agency to make a 'determination.'” Citizens for Responsibility & Ethics in Wash. v. Fed. Election Comm'n, 711 F.3d 180, 188 (D.C. Cir. 2013).

Because my request includes records that should have been reviewed and provided to me by both FDA and HHS over a year ago, I believe appealing to both agencies is appropriate here. Bearing in mind the FOIA and court rulings cited above, it is unacceptable that I have waited over three years for the completion of a straightforward FOIA request.

Please consider my appeal and let me know whether I should redirect my complaints about this FOIA request to the Office of Government Information Services (OGIS) instead.


Sincerely,

Erin Miller

communications.subject: Texas Public Information Act Request: Off-Duty Employment & Bar Incidents
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Texas Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

1. A list of all off-duty employment approvals or disclosures submitted by any Mansfield Police Department employees from January 1, 2022, to December 31, 2024, including business names and locations.

title: Report of suspected tax fraud documents

communications.subject: Illinois Freedom of Information Act. Request: Report of suspected tax fraud documents
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request the following records:

All documents concerning the report of possible tax fraud made pertaining to property located at 16178 E. Franklin Rd Ewing, IL and individuals Melinda and Jestin Squires. The reports are believed to have been made between January and December 2024.

Documents showing number of suspected tax fraud reports made annually and number found substantiated. (To determine if Jefferson County has ever found a tax fraud case).

Records are of public interest to determine how reports of violation of tax laws are applied and enforced and whether there is equal application of the law.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Chris Webster

title: Mineral Settlement Fund Request

communications.subject: West Virginia Freedom of Information Act Request: Mineral Settlement Fund Request
communications.communication:
Dear Lauren, 

Under the West Virginia Freedom of Information Act, §29-B-1-1 et seq., I am requesting an opportunity to inspect or obtain copies of public records related to the budgeting, allocation and spending of opioid lawsuit settlement funds in Mineral County. Specifically, I am seeking;

1.The total amount of opioid settlement funds received by Mineral County so far. 
2.Financial records of all funds that have been allocated and paid to programs or individuals by Mineral County.
3.Evidence of financial invoices, statements, payslips and public records that detail past expenditures of opioid settlement funds in Mineral County.
4.Minutes of public meetings regarding how the opioid settlement funds will be spent.
5.Records of correspondence and/or documentation of review and approval processes regarding the allocation and spending of opioid settlement funds.
6.The names of the individuals who will review and approve applications for funding
7. A blank copy of the application and any documentation of the approval process used in review.

If there are any fees for searching or copying these records, please inform me if the cost will exceed $25. However, I would also like to request a waiver of all fees in that the disclosure of the requested information is in the public interest and will contribute significantly to the public's understanding of how opioid settlement funds are being used in our community. I am a student journalist at West Virginia University, and this information is for educative purposes only. This information is not being sought for commercial purposes. 
The West Virginia Freedom of Information Act requires a response to this request be made within five business days. If access to the records I am requesting will take longer than this amount of time, please contact me with information about when I might expect copies or the ability to inspect the requested records. You can call me at 681-209-0634 or send me an email at fha00001@mix.wvu. My physical address is 1511 University Ave. Morgantown, WV, 26505.

If you deny any or all of this request, please cite each specific exemption you feel justifies the refusal to release the information and notify me of the appeal procedures available to me under the law.

Thank you for considering my request.

Sincerely,
 Faith Abdullah
 681-209-0634
 fha00001@mix.wvu.edu

title: Internal Deliberations on Communication Delay (Feb 3–11, 2025)

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Internal Deliberations on Communication Delay (Feb 3–11, 2025)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

1.	Any internal communications (including emails, text messages, meeting notes, or memos) sent or received by any SPUSD board member, administrator, or district staff between February 3, 2025, and February 18, 2025, that reference:
	•	Deliberations over how to publicly acknowledge or respond to any incident(s) that occurred during the week of February 3–7;
	•	Efforts to delay, manage, or coordinate messaging to parents or the public;
	•	Preparation for the February 11, 2025 board meeting, including decisions about what would or would not be addressed publicly.
2.	Any records—internal or external—reflecting anticipated or actual community records requests related to that same time period.

This request is prompted by Board Member Karissa Adams’s public statement during the February 11, 2025 board meeting. While participating remotely by phone, Ms. Adams stated:

“Let me just start by saying a real big thank you to our staff and our administration… last week we had a little bit more excitement in one week than we would like to have at the school… In this world of communication right now we need to remember that information will be dispelled as it’s necessary and available, and that doesn’t always mean, you know, right this second.”

This statement appears to acknowledge a deliberate delay in communication with families regarding a specific incident or emergency. Notably, no other board member acknowledged the comment, and no one else referred to the incident at any point during the meeting. The session continued without clarification, follow-up, or public discussion—despite the implications of the remark.

For reference, I am including a brief excerpt from the publicly available recording of the meeting:
https://archive.org/download/spusd_02-11-2025/spusd_02-11-2025.mp4

The clip has been lightly zoomed to highlight board member reactions at the moment the comment was made. The fact that a board member raised a potentially serious issue—publicly, on record—and was met with complete silence, including from colleagues physically present in the room, is relevant context for this request.

This statement—and the collective non-response that followed—raises serious questions about what was known internally, when key decisions were made, and how communication with the public was managed at both the administrative and board level.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Michael Rochford

This is a request under the Freedom of Information Act.  I hereby request the following records:

Records relating to Caspar Weinberger (August 18, 1917 – March 28, 2006), who was former Secretary of Defense and Director of the Office of Management and Budget and indicted in the Iran-Contra affair. Sincerely,

Michael Best
