communications.subject: The Missouri Sunshine Law Request: Madison Wathen 2/15/24-2/20/24 (Madison County Medical Examiner & Coroner)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the The Missouri Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

1. Autopsy Report — Madison County Coroner / Medical Examiner

Office name & address (per MuckRock listing):
Madison County Medical Examiner & Coroner
1 Court Square, Fredericktown, MO 63645
Phone: (573) 783‑8336
Fax: (573) 783‑7729 


---

✉️ Autopsy Request Email (send to coroner office or fax)

To: (call to confirm email, typically via county page; fax: 573‑783‑7729)
Subject: Public Records Request – Autopsy Report for Madison Wathen


---

Dear Records Custodian,

Pursuant to Missouri Sunshine Law (Chapter 610, RSMo), I request copies of all autopsy-related records for Madison Wathen, who died February 16, 2024, in Madison County, MO—this includes:

All preliminary/final autopsy reports

Toxicology results

Scene photos and documentation

Medical examiner notes


Requester details:
[Your name]
[Address]
[Email] / [Phone]
Relationship: Concerned citizen / [if applicable: relation]

Please respond within three business days with instructions. If costs apply, notify me before proceeding; I request a waiver of fees in the public interest. Thank you.

Sincerely,
Concerned Citizen. 


---

🚓 2. Troop E / MSHP Investigation Records

Office & Contact Info:
Missouri State Highway Patrol, Troop E – Poplar Bluff HQ
4947 Highway 67 N, Poplar Bluff, MO 63901
Phone: (573) 840‑9500
Fax: (573) 840‑9509 

Custodian of Records — GHQ (Jefferson City):
Lieutenant Gerard “Jerry” Callahan
P.O. Box 1408, Jefferson City, MO 65102-1408
Phone: (573) 526‑6146 or (573) 526‑6167 
Fax: (978) 367‑1187 

---

✉️ MSHP Records Request Email

To: (upload via portal or email to GHQ address)
Subject: Sunshine Request – Troop E Investigation Records – Madison Wathen (Feb 2024)


---

Dear Custodian of Records,

Under Missouri Sunshine Law, please provide all records from Troop E of the MSHP regarding the investigation of Madison Wathen, February 15–17, 2024:

Troop E incident/investigative reports

Trooper notes and statements

Radio dispatch logs and field communications

Any photographs, diagrams, or related records


Please respond with access instructions within 3 business days. If fees apply, notify me before proceeding; I request waiver as it serves the public interest.

Thank you,
Concerned Citizen


---

🧩 Next Steps

1. Confirm coroner office has an email—call (573‑783‑8336) or fax to 573‑783‑7729.


2. Submit MSHP request via their portal or mail/fax to GHQ.


3. Track and follow up—expect an initial response within 3 days.


4. Escalate if needed: file a Sunshine complaint with the AG (sunshinerequest@ago.mo.gov) if you don’t receive a response  .

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

BAILEY PROFFITT

title: Family Military Heritage Research - Army Veteran Service Records

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Family Military Heritage Research - Army Veteran Service Records
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Requesting complete military service records for United States Army veteran Thomas J. Kashuba, D.O.B. November 28 1936, who served in the U.S. Army with estimated service from approximately mid-1950s through 1970s. As his grandson conducting family genealogical research, I am seeking his military personnel file and service documentation.

Records requested:

- Official Military Personnel File (OMPF)
- Service record and assignment history
- Military photographs and portraits
- Awards, decorations, and commendations
- Training records and military education
- Unit assignments and duty stations
- Discharge documentation


FAMILY BACKGROUND: My grandfather Tommy, served as an Army equipment/inventory specialist and I was told that he was stationed at a major base in Washington State. I was named after my grandfather (my middle name is Thomas), reflecting the close relationship we had before his passing when I was 11 years old. I have no surviving immediate family contact and possess no military service documentation or even photographs of his career.

GENEALOGICAL PURPOSE: This request serves family heritage preservation and military service legacy documentation.

Fee waiver requested for family genealogical research and military heritage preservation.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Justin Kashuba

communications.subject: Fwd: Freedom of Information Act Request: Family Military Heritage Research - Army Veteran Service Records

Thank you for submitting your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request to
the National Archives and Records Administration (NARA) via email referral to
foia@nara.gov. We received your request on June 9, 2025.  Your request
concerns the *military service records for United States Army veteran
Thomas J. Kashuba, D.O.B. November 28 1936, who served in the U.S. Army.*

Due to the nature of your inquiry, we are forwarding your request by this
email to the National Personnel Records Center (NPRC) for Military Records
in St. Louis for appropriate handling.  The NPRC will assign your request a
tracking number and respond directly to you.  In the future, if you need to
contact the NPRC, you can do so by mail or fax to the following address:

National Personnel Records Center
1 Archives Drive
St. Louis, Missouri 63138

Telephone:   314-801-0800
Telephone (Toll Free):  1-866-272-6272 (only within the US)
Fax:  314-801-9195

For your reference, below you will find your original submission.

On our website at https://www.archives.gov/veterans/military-service-records
you can find information about requesting Official Military Personnel Files
(OMPFs) that are not yet archival records fully open to the public.  At the
website for the National Archives at St. Louis,
https://www.archives.gov/st-louis/ <https://www.archives.gov/st-louis/%20>,
you will find information about requesting Official Military Personnel
Files that are now archival records open to the public.  The OMPF normally
becomes an archival record 62 years after the date of discharge.

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Act Request: Family Military Heritage Research - Army Veteran Service Records
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Bryan, 

Thank your expeditious and gracious response. My son and I are looking forward to memorializing grandpa Tommy's legacy in both the US Army and Police Career through our records acquisition efforts. 

I would like to bring to your attention that my submission here on Muckrock was directed at the NPRC when I made the request. There is a possibility that the email address was somehow mis-indexed on Muckrock or possibly mis-routed somewhere along the way. I just wanted to bring this to your attention and anyone else that it may benefit. 

Once again please accept my gratitude for your fast and professional response, 

Justin Kashuba

communications.subject: C-0005921493 Request for Military Records
communications.communication:
Hi Justin,

Unfortunately the request that you submitted did not list a contact phone
number so I was not able to reach you.  Your request also did not contain a
mailing address, so I was not able to mail a response letter.  The only
contact information listed in your request is this unusual email address.

I'm sending the only information available based on the extremely limited
information that you provided.  This information is Archival and is
releasable to anyone.

The date of birth does not match but it was only off by one day.  You did
not provide the veteran's Social Security Number, Place of Birth, Date of
Death, Service Number or specific dates of service.

Generally our website is a better option for submitting requests because it
guides you on the information necessary to locate a record-  The link is
listed below for your reference.

https://www.archives.gov/veterans

Thank you,
-- 
Melinda Vaupel
Expert Archives Technician 1D
National Personnel Records Center
1 Archives Drive
St. Louis, MO  63138

Office: (314) 801-0977

Email: Melinda.vaupel@nara.gov

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Act Request: Family Military Heritage Research - Army Veteran Service Records
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Vaupel, 

Thank you for successfully locating my grandfather's military records despite the unconventional submission method. 

I'm unable to access the digital delivery due to technical difficulties with the ID.me verification system. Following your guidance to use more direct communication for future requests, I've sent you a direct email with proper contact information requesting physical delivery of the located records.

NPRC's professionalism has been wonderful and your guidance on proper procedures for military genealogical research has been helpful.

Best regards,
Justin Kashuba
Case: C-0005921493

title: Police disciplinary files (Garfield County Prosecuting Attorney)

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: Police disciplinary files (Garfield County Prosecuting Attorney)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

- Any and all lists, spreadsheets or other organized datasets that detail potential or substantiated allegations of misconduct and/or impeached or impeachable testimony, created under Brady v. Maryland and/or Giglio v. United States.
- Any and all records regarding substantiated allegations of misconduct or violations of internal department policy or criminal law by specific law enforcement officers.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Aspen Ford

communications.subject: RE: Washington Public Records Act Request: Police disciplinary files (Garfield County Prosecuting Attorney)
communications.communication:
Please find the attached records in response to your request for public records. You will find 4 attachments. No documents have been withheld as exempt, but you will find redactions within 1 of the attachments.
File: Clarkston Investigation Pt 2, includes redactions on pages 1, 2 and 11. Pages 1 & 2 are redacted because they contain information regarding a collision/accident report. Accident reports are to remain confidential except to persons that “may have a proper interest therein, including the driver or drivers involved.” Please see RCW 46.52.080.
Page 11 contains redactions of personal information within a Vehicle Registration record. Personal information, including name, address and phone number are exempt from disclosure pursuant to RCW 46.12.635(1), RCW 42.56.070(1), 18 USC § 2721, and/or 18 USC § 2725 (3).
Lastly, a social security number has also been redacted on Page 11. Social Security Numbers are not subject to disclosure pursuant to RCW 42.56.230(5) which exempts “other financial information” as defined in RCW 9.35.005(1), from production under the Public Records Act. “Financial information” in RCW 9.35.005(1) includes social security numbers and tax identification numbers.

Basedon this response your request is now considered closed.

If we have misinterpreted your request or you have other concerns with this response, please feel free to contact us.

Respectfully,


MATT L. NEWBERG
Garfield County Prosecuting Attorney
809 Columbia St./P.O. Box 820
Pomeroy, WA  99347
Office: (509) 843-3082
Fax: (509) 843-2337

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: PRA Request: SchoolMint
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

- All contracts, licenses, MOUs, MOAs, data agreements, letters of intent, State of Work documents, Scope of Work documents, and other agreement documents with SchoolMint Inc that were active any time between 1/1/2022 and 12/18/2024.
- All financial documents or records of financial transactions, exchanges or obligations related to SchoolMint Inc. Responsive materials include all invoices, bills, receipts, check stubs, or any other records, including those possessed in an electronic format.
- A copy of all training materials, including but not limited to any handouts, workbooks, assessments, presentations, slides, videos, audio files, or other materials, either developed in-house or provided to the agency pertaining to the agency's use of SchoolMint Inc products.
- A copy of all agency manuals either developed in-house or provided to the agency pertaining to the agency's use of SchoolMint Inc products.
- A copy of all agency policies and procedures either developed in-house or provided to the agency pertaining to the agency's use of SchoolMint Inc products.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

e

Hello,

Thank you for your reply.  Although you state the request was submitted on December 18, 2024, we did not receive the request until March 31, 2025.  Government Code section 7922.535 requires that a public agency, within ten days of receiving a request, make an initial determination of whether it has non-privileged, non-exempt documents in its possession responsive to the request and offer a reasonable time frame in which it will produce the records

Thus, you can expect to receive a response to your request on or before April 10, 2025.

title: "Public Masturbation Deterrent Infrastructure"

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: "Public Masturbation Deterrent Infrastructure"
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

All documents, memoranda, emails, and Teams messages that reference the phrase "public masturbation deterrent infrastructure" since January 1, 2024, as referenced in local reporting such as https://www.king5.com/article/news/local/seattle/seattle-residents-sue-city-rampant-masturbation-indecent-acts-denny-blaine-park/281-a82cbdae-843a-40f7-b401-cfde18be716a

Apologies for the bizarre request!

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Rose Terse

Dear Rose Terse, 
 
Records in response to your public disclosure request C224039-042925 received on April 29, 2025 are now available. The cost for the records is as follows: 
 
Invoice Number: INV25-C224039-1 
Total: $1.25 
 
To pay online, please follow these steps: 
 Please note that you will need to disable any pop-up blockers to make a payment using the system. 
 
  * Navigate to the Public Records Request Center. 
  * Select 'My Records Request Center'. 
  * Select 'View My Requests'. You may be asked to login. 
  * Find this request: C224039-042925. 
  * Select the 'View Invoices' button. 
 
  * Opens a pop-up window showing your invoice: INV25-C224039-1. 
  * Click on the invoice and then the 'Pay Now' button. 
  * Continue processing your payment. 
  * Select 'Done'. 
  * Once the payment process is done, you are returned to the Public Records Request Center. 
  * After your payment is successful you will receive an email from our payments center. 
Once your payment has been approved, we will send you an email with instructions on how to download your records. Note that City staff must manually upload records. Records will be available one to two business days after payment. 
 
Please let your public disclosure officer (PDO) know if you are unable to pay online; your PDO will work with you on alternative ways to make your payment. 
 
You have 30 days from today's date to pay for your records. If the City does not receive your payment within this time period, your request will be considered abandoned, and you will need to submit a new request.

To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

- Any and all lists, spreadsheets or other organized datasets that detail potential or substantiated allegations of misconduct and/or impeached or impeachable testimony, created under Brady v. Maryland and/or Giglio v. United States.
- Any and all records regarding substantiated allegations of misconduct or violations of internal department policy or criminal law by specific law enforcement officers.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

communications.subject: [Document Released to Requester] Clallam County WA public records request #25-931
communications.communication:
Clallam County WA

************************************************************************


Documents have been released for record request #25-931 along with the following message:

Following a reasonable search, Clallam County has completed the assembly and duplication of all identifiable public records that respond to your request. At this time, we believe that we have responded to your request in full by making the records available to you in the Records Center.



This request is now closed. As such, we do not intend to further address this request and the PRA's one-year statute of limitations to seek judicial review has started to run.



If you believe that there are other records in existence that should have been released to you in response to this request, please notify the Public Records Office as soon as possible.



Pursuant Clallam County Policy 321.17, fees for records requests shall be waived when the total fee for the request is under ten dollars. Since the total fee for this request is under ten dollars, no payment is due at this time.



Some of the records that are being provided to you have been redacted in part pursuant to applicable law. The redactions appear as black boxes on various pages of the responsive documents. Within the redaction box there is overlay text designating a code for the statutory exemption applicable to the redacted information. Brief explanations of the basis for the redactions are provided on the redaction log. As you review these responsive records, you can refer to the explanations listed in the redaction l to identify the exemption and its applicability.



The Public Records Office has attempted to apply consistent redactions on documents that contain the same information. In the event that you locate documents that contain redactions that are not applied consistently, please contact the Public Records Office. Please also contact the Public Records Office if you believe records were improperly redacted or withheld.



Pursuant to the Clallam County Administrative Policies and Procedures, any person who objects to the partial denial or redaction of a request for a Public Record may petition the Public Records Officer for a review of that decision. The petition must be in writing and include the petitioner’s name and contact information. The petition must be filed within 10 days of the denial.



If you have difficulty downloading your records, click HERE for assistance. Please contact the Public Records Office if you have any questions or if you have difficultly accessing the electronic records. You can reach our office by responding to this message or by calling the phone number below.



Sincerely,



Jesse Major

Public Records Officer

Public Records, Information Technology

Desk 360-417-2423

title: Water Asset Management funds correspondence

communications.subject: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Water Asset Management funds correspondence
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

1. All email correspondence, with attachments, mentioning "Water Property Investors," "Water Property Investor II," or "Water Property Investor III." 

2. Pitch decks, prospectuses, or any other materials provided to NMERB by the the above funds for consideration of potential investments.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 15 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Julia Rock

communications.subject: RE: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Water Asset Management funds correspondence
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Rock,

I am responding to your email yesterday requesting any additional info regarding the source of delays on this request. Please be assured that we make every effort to respond promptly to every request. However, we must also ensure that we are diligent and accurate in our reply. Thus, when obtained, all documents and emails must be reviewed. Additionally, we must rely on the state agency that controls the entire state email system to identify and provide the emails requested. As you can imagine, the process takes time.

As to an estimated response date, in our letter of August 1, 2023, we noted that we intend to respond by September 6, 2023.

Thank you for your patience and please feel free to contact me if you have further questions.

Respectfully,

communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Rock and Ms. Burns,

Thank you for your inquiry and please accept our apologies for the delay.

As Mr. Scroggins noted in his August 3, 2023 email regarding our projected response, we always try to be prompt.  But as you might guess, the request references a large number of records.  As he said, we must thoroughly review all records to identify and obtain the responsive documents from both external and internal sources.  It is a complex and time-consuming process.

I am confident that we will have documents ready to provide on or before the December 6th, 2023, date noted in our recent communication.

Thank you for your continued patience!
Regards,
Renee

title: Late Show with Stephen Colbert FCC Complaints

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Late Show with Stephen Colbert FCC Complaints
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

All FCC complaints received regarding The Late Show with Stephen Colbert on CBS from September 1, 2024 through the date this request is processed.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Jed Rosenzweig
